</ab>
</div>
<div type="textpart" subtype="face" n="b">
<ab>
<lb n="2"/><expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>onum</ex></expan>
</ab>
</div>
<div type="textpart" subtype="face" n="c">
<ab><expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>edit</ex></expan>.</ab></div></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Chio gave this as a gift.</p></div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>One of eight Carrara marble vessels dedicated by Chio at the Sanctuary of Diana
                    Nemorensis. It is missing the beak of one griffin. It is one of a pair with
                    PA.Phil.UP.UM.L.MS3449. The plinth may be modern. The shape of the cauldron
                    imitates the Greek bronze wine-mixing bowls of the archaic period. The vessel is
                    solid and so could not have been used as a container. As for the inscription,
                    the precise meaning of 'Chio' is unclear: Guldager Bilde argues that the name
                    Chio is a Latinized form of Χίων, 'from Chios', and therefore he must have been
                    a wealthy freedman. Steinbauer (in Bentz 1998/99) is not as certain of the
                    dedicant's social status, but agrees with Guldager Bilde on the derivation of
                    the name. Guldager Bilde also suggests that the vessel was used in a hero-cult
                    context in honor of Hippolytos, given the funerary associations of the griffin
                    decoration. Bentz argues instead that the group was dedicated in honor of a
                    victory at the ludi Apollinares.</p></div>
            
            
